      "definition": "An integer is nothing but a row of bits, and the bitwise operators work on that row directly: `<<` and `>>` slide the bits left or right, `&` keeps only the bits where a mask has a 1, and `|` merges two patterns. Hex is the human shorthand for those rows — one hex digit is exactly four bits, so one byte is always exactly two hex digits.",
      "code": "let key = (5 << 3) | 2        // pack two numbers into one:\nprint(key)                    // 42\nprint(String(key, radix: 2))  // 101010 — 5 slid left, 2 in the gap\nprint(key >> 3, key & 0b111)  // 5 2    — unpacked again\n\nprint(String(300, radix: 16)) // 12c — hex: four bits per digit\nprint(0xFF & 300)             // 44  — mask: keep only the low byte\n\nlet v: UInt32 = 0x1122_3344\nwithUnsafeBytes(of: v) { print($0.map { String($0, radix: 16) }) }\n// [\"44\", \"33\", \"22\", \"11\"] — little-endian: lowest byte stored first",
      "underlying": "b0-01 said a variable is a box of bytes; this loop looks inside the byte. Shifting left by n multiplies by 2ⁿ because each bit position is worth twice its neighbor: `5 << 3` turns `101` into `101000` (40), and OR-ing in `2` (`010`) fills the vacated low positions — 42 is `101010`, executed above. Nothing magical was 'packed': the two numbers simply occupy disjoint bit positions of one integer, which is why `>> 3` and `& 0b111` recover them exactly. Masking works because of AND's truth table — `1 & x` passes x through, `0 & x` clears it — so `0b111` keeps three low bits, `0x7F` keeps seven, `0xFF` keeps a byte. Executed: `0xFF & 300` = 44, the low byte of `1 0010 1100`. Masks SELECT bits; setting them is OR's job.\n\nHex earns its place because the translation to bits is positional, digit by digit: `A` is `1010` wherever it stands, so `0xAC` reads as `1010 1100` on sight, while the same value as decimal 172 hides its bits behind long division. Four bits per digit means two digits per byte — that's why memory dumps, wire captures, and crash addresses all arrive in hex pairs.\n\nLast: the bytes of a multi-byte integer sit in the box in an ORDER. ARM (and x86) is little-endian — least-significant byte first — executed: `0x1122_3344` lives in memory as `44 33 22 11`. Inside Swift you never notice, because the value is just the value; the order becomes real the moment bytes cross a boundary — a file, a socket, `withUnsafeBytes`. That's why every wire format declares an order up front (preview: Block 7's protobuf sends its fixed-width numbers little-endian, while classic TCP/IP headers are big-endian, 'network byte order').",
