      "modelAnswer": "TCP guarantees the bytes I write arrive complete and in the order I wrote them, over a connection named by the 4-tuple of source and destination IP and port. It deliberately does not preserve message boundaries — it is one continuous byte stream, so framing messages is the job of the protocol above, which is why HTTP has Content-Length and gRPC length-prefixes every message. A successful send() proves only that the bytes were copied into my kernel's local buffer — not that they were delivered, and not that the connection is even still alive; a dead connection often surfaces only on the write after the one that 'succeeded'.",
