      "solution": "(a) SAFE. Names never travel — the wire only ever carried the number 2. Cost is compile-time only: regenerated Swift renames the property, call sites get fixed by the compiler.\n\n(b) BREAKS — silently. `int32` and `sint32` share wire type 0, so nothing errors: old clients' discount 1 arrives at the new decoder as -1 (executed), and every negative discount from new senders reads as a huge wrong number on old clients. Corrupt values, zero exceptions.\n\n(c) SAFE. Old clients skip field 5 by wire type; when old clients send, new decoders fill `note` with `\"\"`. Both directions degrade gracefully.\n\n(d) LANDMINE. Nothing breaks today — old senders' field 4 just gets skipped. The damage comes later: without `reserved 4;`, someone reuses the number, and three-week-old (or year-old) builds still emitting the old field 4 suddenly have their bytes interpreted as the new field. The fix is one line, and it belongs in THIS PR.",
      "explanation": "Notice the shape of every wrong answer: protobuf compatibility failures are never loud. Skip-by-wire-type makes decoding succeed at all costs, which converts contract mistakes from crashes into quiet zeros, empty strings, and wrong numbers — the hardest class of bug to notice. If you need loud, you add it yourself with validation above the codec."
