      "code": "// executed — resolution's artifact (Package.resolved):\n// { \"identity\": \"swift-atomics\",\n//   \"location\": \"https://github.com/apple/swift-atomics.git\",\n//   \"state\": { \"revision\": \"0442cb5a…\", \"version\": \"1.3.1\" } }\n//   ← a transitive dep, pinned by COMMIT HASH, not just version\n\n// executed — the linking fork, same library both ways:\n// dynamic: otool -L app_dyn  →  libGreet.dylib (dependency edge)\n//          delete the dylib   →  dyld: 'Library not loaded: libGreet.dylib'\n// static:  otool -L app_static → no Greet — the code is INSIDE the binary\n//          the dylib can vanish; the app doesn't notice",
      "underlying": "Resolution first. Your manifest declares REQUIREMENTS (`from: \"1.3.0\"` = up to next major, per semver); the resolver walks the whole graph — including dependencies' dependencies (the executed swift-atomics pin arrived via swift-nio, nothing this package asked for by name) — finds one version per package satisfying everyone, and writes the lockfile: identity, location, version AND commit hash (executed — the hash is the real pin; tags can move, commits can't). The lockfile is the reproducibility contract: committed to git, it makes every machine and CI build the same sources; `resolve` obeys it, `update` rewrites it — and 'works on my machine, fails in CI' dependency bugs are almost always one machine holding a different lock. Version CONFLICTS are resolution's honest failure: two packages demanding incompatible majors of a third have no solution, and the fix is negotiation (bump one) — not force.\n\nLinking is where 'what ends up in the app bundle' gets decided, and the executed pair is the whole taxonomy. STATIC: the library's code is copied into the executable at link time — otool shows no dependency, nothing extra to load at launch, the lib file itself can vanish post-build. DYNAMIC: the executable records a dependency edge (executed: `libGreet.dylib` in otool -L) and dyld loads it at launch — the executed deletion producing `dyld: Library not loaded`, which is the same crash users see as 'app won't open' when a framework is missing from the bundle or an install is corrupted. The trade: static costs binary size but zero launch work; dynamic costs dyld time per framework at launch (b6-07's measured pre-main tax) and enables sharing between app and extensions (one framework, two processes — the app-plus-widget case where dynamic earns its keep). Note the honest executed detail: our tiny lib produced identical file sizes — the size argument is real only at real scale. SPM defaults to static where it can (`.automatic`); mergeable libraries (modern toolchains) blur the line further by letting release builds merge dynamic deps statically — documented.\n\nCocoaPods does the same two jobs with different machinery, visible in the artifacts the work app carries: `Podfile.lock` is its lockfile (same contract — commit it, diff it in review); integration happens by MUTATING your build — it generates a Pods project, wraps everything in an `.xcworkspace` (why 'always open the workspace'), and injects xcconfig files that your own configs must `#include` (the b11-01 tie: 'my xcconfig broke the build' usually means that include line died). Frameworks vs static libs in Pods follows `use_frameworks!`. The philosophical difference is WHERE they live: SPM is resolution-plus-build inside Xcode's own build system; CocoaPods is a build-system co-owner — powerful, and the reason removing it cleanly is a project surgery.",
