      "underlying": "The split exists because 'the app is on screen' stopped being one fact: iPad multi-window means one PROCESS hosting several UI instances of the same app. So responsibilities divide sharply. AppDelegate keeps what is process-wide: didFinishLaunching (dependency setup, b8-01's container), push token delivery (b9-03 — the token is per-install, not per-window), background events (b9-06's permits). SceneDelegate gets what is per-UI-instance: `scene(_:willConnectTo:options:)` — where the window is CREATED and the root installed (in scene-based apps the storyboard/root wiring happens here or via the manifest), plus the foreground/background dance per scene. The executed manifest shows the wiring is b10-01's pattern again — a delegate CLASS NAME in a plist, resolved at runtime — and the executed Catalyst crash from b2-20's verification ('NSApplication has not been created yet' when creating a bare UIWindow headless) is the architectural fact surfacing: windows are scene citizens now, which is also why `UIApplication.shared.keyWindow` deprecated into 'which scene's window do you mean?'.\n\nThe lifecycle mapping extends b2-13 rather than replacing it (deeper-not-repeat): the PROCESS still walks not-running → foreground → background → suspended (b2-13's machine, b9-06's freezer), but scene states ride on top — each scene independently connects → foregrounds → backgrounds → DISCONNECTS. Disconnection is the new event worth respect: the system may disconnect a background scene to reclaim memory WITHOUT killing the process (b2-13's silent kill got a milder sibling), destroying the UI while your singletons live on. `sceneDidDisconnect` is the cleanup hook, and any 'the app restarted but my object graph didn't' weirdness on iPad is exactly this — one lifecycle died, the other didn't.\n\nRestoration is how disconnection stays invisible to users: each scene hands the system an `NSUserActivity` describing WHERE it is (executed: an activityType plus a userInfo dictionary — 'order-detail, A-2319'), via `stateRestorationActivity(for:)`; on reconnection the activity comes back in the connection options and the app REBUILDS that UI — which is b10-02's Router earning its keep once more (the activity names a route; the Router materializes it), and the same NSUserActivity type doubles for Handoff, Spotlight, and deep links, making 'describe your screens as data' one investment paying four times. For single-window phone apps the manifest often declares multiple-scenes false (executed manifest) and the SceneDelegate is a thin ceremony — but the ceremony is load-bearing the day the app meets an iPad, and understanding WHICH delegate owns an event is this loop's entire practical yield.",
