      "underlying": "The executed comparison bug has a real outage genealogy: apps that string-compared versions worked for years — until the marketing version crossed from 1.9 to 1.10 and the check decided every up-to-date user was ancient, walling THEM behind the forced-update screen (or letting genuinely old clients through). Segments must compare as NUMBERS — the executed `.numeric` compare is Foundation handing you the correct tool — and the check must use the right identity: `CFBundleShortVersionString` is the marketing version gates and stores speak; `CFBundleVersion` is the monotonically-climbing build number CI stamps (b11-06) and TestFlight distinguishes builds by. Confusing them gates on a number the server never heard of.\n\nThe fleet is the fact that makes strategy necessary. A release reaches users through review (days, not hours — plan for it), optionally a PHASED rollout (documented: automatic delivery ramps over seven days — 1%, 2%, 5%… — pausable mid-ramp, which is your safety valve: a day-two crash spike means PAUSE, fix, resubmit, not push-on), and then adoption's long tail: months later, meaningful cohorts still run old versions. Consequences run in both directions. The backend must serve every live version — which is b7-02's schema discipline promoted to policy (append fields, never repurpose; version the breaking changes) — and when an old version must genuinely die, the server enforces it too (a graceful minimum-version rejection at the API layer — gRPC's FAILED_PRECONDITION with a readable message), because clients that predate your version-gate feature can't obey a gate they never learned to check.\n\nThe gate itself is a composition of earlier loops. It rides remote config fetched early but NON-blocking (b6-07: the launch path doesn't wait on a network call), cached with a TTL (b6-03), and — the load-bearing decision — failing OPEN: config unreachable means proceed normally, because the alternative is the self-inflicted outage where your config server's bad hour bricks every launch behind an update wall nobody can pass. (Fail-open's honest cost: during an outage, old clients roam ungated — which is why the SERVER-side minimum-version check is the backstop, and the client gate is UX, not security.) The blocking screen deep-links to the store (`itms-apps://…`); the nudge is dismissible and rate-limited, because a nag that fires every launch trains users to hate updates. And the honest ceiling on all of it: forced update is a MONTHS-long lever, never an emergency brake — review plus adoption is the minimum latency — so the real emergency tools are the ones that work without shipping: feature flags to disable a broken path, server-side fixes, and the protocol compatibility that made old clients safe to leave running in the first place.",
